United States: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It even becomes comical, the diligent effort with which Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of wise, reproduces his predecessor’s strategy on the Afghan issue, which he himself considered simple.
When he ended up sweating his long-awaited doctrine, it turned out that he had copied it on carbon paper since Bush’s Iraqi script three years ago.
Not only did he use the phrase "like in Iraq" several times in the text itself, he did not hesitate to use the title of Bush's January 2007 speech as the title of his own speech: "A New Way Forward."
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush’s idea of sending new reinforcements into a civil war-consumed Iraq as “irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its consequences.”
The following months, however, have shown that Bush's strategy, emanating from the recommendations of the campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to succeed to such an extent that the newspapers currently do not speak at all of Iraq.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, that said, objectively speaking, he left his successor in a much more favorable final situation than we could have hoped.
Barack Obama hopes the miracle will happen again in Afghanistan
It was once again campaign commanders who asked for an increase in the military contingent, including Afghan Operation Commander General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the White House's reluctance despite subordination habits.
He asked for 40,000 men in order to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months but, in the absence of a better option, he cheated at least the general of 10,000 soldiers.
He succeeded in withdrawing the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though it originally counted on 10,000.
The most problematic thing about Obama's entire strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and to complete this whole process within three years. The whole Obama doctrine brings more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt the fact that a half-increase will bear the same fruits as the increase in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor the agreements.
The Afghan situation stands out by the exact opposite - no one can be counted on and no treaty is respected.
In these circumstances, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing leaders on a day-to-day basis according to their arrangements.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain only dust in the eyes behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is unusually complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups in view of the lack of clarity on the relationships, which are still complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a “quick state to act,” which is the basic purpose of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy makes him perplexed by his voluntarism.
In the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is currently on the verge of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and out-of-reality heart can be persuaded that the small soldiers sent into the tumult of the war with a view to their "rapid return home" will bring there a true miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will consider it as the indirect confession of the American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans’ willingness to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is oriented towards the negative.
European politicians do not know and do not want to explain to their voters why security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the Americans will face the very difficult question of resolving the problem through the use of military force.
This will have to be answered, for example, when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
Any such solution will, however, lead to a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only problem for Obama is the fact that there are three years until the presidential elections, and therefore there is still enough time for him to work on a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
