However, their consumption has a number of side effects.
In addition, the suppression of this multiplication has the effect of the development of so-called resistant viruses on which the drugs no longer have an effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the V<0xC5><0xA0>CHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg paves the way for a way to deal with resistance to the virus.
They have shown that substances called metallocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metallocarboranes are an assembly of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers' work leads them to discover new "enhanced" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their bindings to virus proteins.
Metallocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are formed by the boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV virus division caused by HIV protease, there would be no mature infectious particles of the virus.
If we stop HIV protease, we will also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the researchers said in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In their work published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of combinations where two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic link, which is then systematically modified.
A little weaker but more reliable.
The efficacy of this series of substances on HIV proteases has been tested in test pieces as well as on its resistant variants, obtained from HIV-infected patients.
On the current version of the enzyme, the effect of metallocarboranes is not as strong as on clinical drugs, however, it does not weaken on the resistant versions against which common drugs are often ineffective.
Metallocarboranes, with their unique mechanism of action and other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications, are therefore interesting combinations to examine further in order to move towards the development of effective HIV drugs, says Pavlína <0xC5><0x98>ezá<0xC4><0x8D>ová, director of the structural biology laboratory of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry.
