Pneumococcal vaccination will be free and optional
Pneumococcal vaccination will reverse old habits as early as January.
It will be the first to be free and at the same time optional for families.
There are already voices rising, saying mandatory vaccination would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of free pneumococcal vaccination are culminating.
The pharmaceutical institute already defines for vaccines the maximum prices that health insurance will pay.
Specialists also see clear in the vaccination process.
A new vaccination.
Free vaccines for children in August.
Since January, children born last year from 2 August can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococcal infections.
The condition is that they have not yet been vaccinated.
If you started vaccination last year or earlier, you will have to pay for the following vaccinations yourself.
The first dose of the vaccine should be administered between the 3rd and 5th month of the child.
Last year already a quarter of families voluntarily vaccinated their children against pneumococcal infections.
However, the parents paid 1600 crowns or more for a dose.
Vaccination of the youngest requires four doses.
Experts estimate that health insurance companies spend between 300 and 450,000 crowns a year on vaccine doses.
However, they save on the medical care that unvaccinated children would need.
Until now, the state has spent about 500,000 crowns a year on all children’s vaccinations.
The reimbursed vaccination was introduced with the "Janota package".
Pneumococcus is the cause of inflammation of the middle ear but also serious infections including inflammation of the brain and blood poisoning.
According to hospital surveys, there are up to 28 deaths of children under the age of 10 caused by pneumococcal infections.
Apart from the Czech Republic, some 40 other countries have introduced the refunded vaccination.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
There are opinions on a possible vaccination obligation in the future.
As of January, it must be settled by insurance and optional.
For example, the president of the association Nahlas Rudolf Kalovský indicated that compulsory vaccination would be more positive.
Its association has long promoted pneumococcal vaccination.
At an international conference in which our association participated, the specialists were not really satisfied that we have an optional vaccination.
It's not ideal.
On the other hand, we are pleased to have been able to impose at least this.
I think this is a direction that must now be followed, Kalovský said.
But the health ministry does not want to change the pneumococcal vaccination process.
We are absolutely not considering it at the moment, said its spokesman Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>.
Optional vaccination has its disadvantages, doctors say.
Hana Cabrnochová, president of the Specialized Society of Pediatricians, acknowledges that vaccination based on volunteerism is flawed.
If all children were vaccinated, we could consider a reduction in vaccination renewals "In the situation where the vaccine costs such a sum I understand the decision making vaccination optional," Cabrnochová said.
As of next year, more than 80 percent of new parents will have their infants vaccinated.
Pneumococcal vaccination also marks a break from the fact that it is the first child vaccination that is funded by insurance and not by the state.
Cabrnochová explains that insurance should release funds for prevention, thus saving on possible future medical care.
Doctors will have to buy their own products.
This, however, is related to the concerns of pediatric practitioners, which concern the purchase of vaccines.
The original intention was to have the vaccines purchased by insurance, with doctors receiving them in the same way as other vaccine products provided by the state.
However, some MEPs feared that this would allow insurance companies to "deduct the amounts of health insurance".
Thus, doctors will have to buy the products and wait for insurance to reimburse them.
It is estimated that pediatricians will have to invest nearly 40,000 crowns per month in vaccines, which is a significant amount.
It will be far from easy, according to Cabrnochová.
