In the aging China, a change of direction
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters preaching to them, "The Mother Earth is too tired to accommodate more children" and "One more baby is one more grave."
They learned the lesson so well that the authorities of the Shanghai Government, alarmed by the insufficient birth rate in their city and by the aging population, radically changed direction this summer and began encouraging young couples to have more than one child; their reaction was instant and firm: never.
We have already given all our time and energy to one child.
We have no seconds left, said Wang, 31, Human Resources Director, who has an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, creating two generations of unique children notoriously with good cheeks and spoiled, dubbed the "little emperors", a population crisis threatens the country.
According to the UN, the average birth rate fell by 1.8 children per couple compared to six when the policy was implemented.
The distribution of the population, while the number of residents aged 60 and over is projected to explode, from 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 percent by 2050, is well above the overall average of about 20 percent.
This imbalance is even worse in rich coastal cities with a highly educated population, such as Shanghai.
Last year, people aged 60 and over accounted for nearly 22 percent of the registered resident population in Shanghai, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, Director of the Shanghai Municipal Population and Family Planning Commission, said fertile couples must have babies in order to “help reduce the proportion of the aging population and prevent a shortage of labor in the future.”
Shanghai is about to become "as old - but not as rich, however - as developed countries such as Japan and Sweden," she said.
Gradual mitigation
Drafted in the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is to date undoubtedly the most controversial obligation introduced by the communist government.
Couples who violate this policy may have to pay huge fines -- up to three times their annual income -- and face discrimination in the workplace.
Chinese authorities have given the police the duty to help the country avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while human rights lawyers have denounced abuses in the implementation of this policy.
In rural areas, some officials forced pregnant women with a second child to abort.
In addition, many couples have resorted to selective abortions leading to an abnormally high boy-girl ratio.
In recent years, the authorities responsible for the population have gradually softened their position on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they granted more exceptions to the rule -- including for city residents, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where men and women are already single children -- and in 2007, they softened many of their harsh slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at Beijing University, said central government authorities have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the partners is a single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
In no time, posters encouraging families to have only one child were replaced by copies of regulations detailing who is entitled to have a second child and how to apply for authorization.
The city government sent family planning officials and volunteers to meet couples at their homes and slide leaflets under their doors.
He also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who wish to have more than one child.
According to the head of family planning, the response was disappointing.
Disappointing response
Although officials in a rural suburban city in Shanghai say they saw an increase in requests for records from couples wishing a second child after the campaign launched, the more urban district reported that there was no change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, still receives only four to five requests per month.
Shanghai officials, disappointed, say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to be only about 165,000 -- slightly higher than in 2009 but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee in Shanghai’s Caolu commune, said financial considerations are probably the main reason many people don’t want to have more children.
They want to provide for their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would love to have two children and that they are legally allowed to do so.
But like many Chinese, they only have the minimum health insurance and life insurance given by the government.
Without social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
Westerners mistakenly view the one-child policy as a rights issue, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple’s first child.
It's true, we're being robbed of the chance to have more than one child.
But the problem is not just the law.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, Head of Human Resources, said that she only wanted a single child because she was one herself. "We were the center of the family and used to have everyone taking care of us."
We’re not used to taking care of someone else and we really don’t want to take care of others.”
Chen Zijian, 42 years old and owner of a translation company, says it more boldly.
For middle-class couples working in pairs, which lower the birth rate, he says, you have to be selfish to succeed.
People in their 20s or 30s grew up seeing their parents fight in the early days of capitalist China and don’t want to have that lifestyle themselves, he says.
Even a single child takes a lot of time from his parents, he says.
A mother must give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are the space issues -- "You have to change your apartment" -- and the planning -- "When your child is only 9 months old, you have to write his resume to get a place in the best kindergarten."
Most of his friends are ready for this experience once, Chen says, but not two.
Our generation is the first to benefit from a higher standard of living, he says.
We don’t want to make too many sacrifices.
The United Nations Group has draft plans for emission reduction
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- so far characterized by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- came back under the ramp on Friday, due to the release of a document highlighting the ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations supporting most of the charge, in the next 40 years.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as well as shed light on the way forward.
But it has been seen as a major step forward in time-consuming negotiations, with more than 100 leaders from around the world arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Written by a special UN working group, the text does not say how much rich countries would give to the poor to support global warming, in the long run and in the long run.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed economies and new emerging economies could reduce their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of the global temperature rise that officials would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Representative in Washington of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what UN Executive Secretary-General on climate change Yvo de Boer described as “the full picture.”
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020, from 25 percent to 45 percent from 1990 levels, while major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 percent to 30 percent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also revived negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand flooding and drought or to prevent deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, U.S. Climate Negotiation Representative, rejected any discussion requiring the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, compared to the voluntary efforts of major emerging economies, if they were not financed by developed countries.
This change is a signal that the Obama administration is getting harder on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States is not going to sign an agreement without efforts and actions from major developing countries, Stern said, who also regretted that the text does not insist enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his remarks an hour after China's deputy foreign minister He Yafei said the US chief negotiator either lacked "good sense" or was "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier in the week that the United States would not financially help China to fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major world powers at stake, flaws have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about rescuing individual economies than rescuing the planet, with China and the United States quarreling over their respective obligations while poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that major powers are fighting over who should bear the costs of decreasing greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to hold major emitters accountable for their actions.
It’s really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, said Ulate, who is also Climate Adviser for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they will continue to push for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most key participants say negotiations will lead to at least a political agreement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, head of the European Commission's climate unit, said the action of small island states has "put political pressure on the entire political process", partly because they are now unified and they are calling on emerging economies such as China and India to act.
Debates became an urgent matter, as delegates focused on solving most of the outstanding issues before heads of government reached an agreement.
Senior officials such as the Indian Minister of the Environment, Jairam Ramesh, and the Chinese Deputy Minister got off their planes and rushed to the Bella Center building to attend closed-door meetings and news conferences in order to make claims that will be investigated in the following week.
The real picture of the rally -- where 13,000 people enter and leave the Congress Hall every day -- guitar-playing activists show nighttime shows mocking countries that they say betray each other and that proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than via email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the court of the greats, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice-President for Global Policy at Conservation International.
The heavy trucks are coming.
