For its part, the Prosecutor's Office of Nanterre once again ruled that the complainant was not admissible to act, especially since a guardianship judge has refused in recent days to grant her application to initiate judicial protection proceedings for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full capacity for legal action, she is not under protection and has no guardian.
No one else has to act in his place,” prosecutor Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney said.
The court finally decided that it would rule once the trial had taken place on the admissibility of Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers.
Management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been futile...
For more than ten years, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees, reminds the position of companies vis-<0xC3><0xA0>-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a matter of making employees adhere to determined "values" from above as it was in the past, to impose on consumers products thought by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering the markets in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from the factors of customer preferences regularly comes back!
Demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects executives in particular.
This demobilization seriously jeopardizes the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI "requires from all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires from employees a commitment that authoritarian management revenues totally contradict.
That’s why we call for a managerial revolution that would be to put employees at the center of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – like the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – incite this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all because I have been able to find that, in the face of a new situation, every structure finally arrives, after many detours, to do priority... what it has always done.
- Secondly, because authoritarianism - one of the pathologies of power - grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Coming from major engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the US "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "sic" of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr reinforces the leaders in a position of mechanistic governance, inappropriate to today's world.
Identifying and Measuring Mobilizing Factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises requires adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental observation: for employees, commitment to the company is possible only if it clearly appears as a way to realize part of their dreams, ambitions, projects.
Currently, only studies from the Functional Motive Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their business based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life plans.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilizing factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resources management "in place".
They thus create a favourable ground for the concerted development of robust and efficient economic intelligence.
Oslo Speech: 'Just War' Is Worth Right-wing Praise to Obama
The U.S. right on Friday welcomed Barack Obama’s speech in Oslo, pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize defended the concept of “just war” against U.S. enemies.
The Conservatives, who brokered the award to Mr. Obama on October 9, applauded the presidential speech this time, like Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, said Ms. Palin, a right-wing Republican, to USA Today, adding that she herself had addressed the topic of “sometimes necessary” war in her recently published memoirs.
War is, of course, the last thing the Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
We need to stop these terrorists all over there, she said.
Obama, who inherited the two wars of his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, worked in Oslo on Thursday to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send an additional 30,000 troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done “very good work” in Oslo.
I found that the speech was really very good, welcomed the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential statement.
On some sides, I found this speech quite historic, said Mr. Gingrich, interviewed on the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former elected official, considered by some to be a possible Republican nomination candidate for the 2012 presidential election, said he was delighted to have seen “a left-wing president” remind members of the Nobel Committee “that they would not be free and could not award a peace prize if the use of force did not exist.”
For Michael Gerson, former pen of George W. Bush's reconverted columnist at the Washington Post, Mr. Obama delivered "a very American speech."
In addition to presenting himself as a "citizen of the world" as "he always does," "he spoke like an American president," reminding Europeans "that they live in a security bubble that they have not created and that they do not do much to preserve it," Gerson said.
Among the few right-wingers not to be convinced, a Bush-era hawk, former UN ambassador John Bolton, called the speech "ternate, bulging and uninspired" on the National Review Online website.
On the left of the president, Democratic representative Dennis Kucinich was alarmed to see Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
When war is enveloped in the notion of justice, it is easy to justify the slaughter of innocent people, he warned.
The centre-left press, however, remained praiseworthy in the place of the president.
The Los Angeles Times, while continuing to think that the Nobel Prize was awarded prematurely to Mr. Obama, called his speech “overproduction” even for a speaker known for his talent.
