The first snow can fall
What Wolfgang Brauburger wants is a harsh winter.
But the head of the road clearing and sandblasting service (FES) states that it is not to bother citizens.
This is simply so that agents can test the technology of vehicles and learn how to master them well.
And according to the meteorologists, this could well be for this weekend.
More than 300 agents and 120 vehicles are ready to tackle snow and ice.
The ESF follows a very elaborate plan here.
Mr. Brauburger explains that as soon as it starts to snow on the city of Frankfurt and temperatures drop below zero, large sandblasting vehicles run 20 main routes (called A routes).
This includes high-traffic streets, main arteries, such as the Neue Weg and the Hanauer Landstraße.
Also included are fire access, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloping streets such as Atzelbergstraße.
ESF officers begin their service at three o'clock in the morning.
If necessary, the 1040 kilometers of roads must be salted with a road foundation that adheres well, in a maximum of 3 hours.
This is why the FES service starts at 3 a.m. "so that the roads are cleared when the traffic of the daily migrations begins".
It gets harder when the snow starts falling at 7:30 in the morning.
This poses problems, the head of the road clearing and sandblasting department tells us "because no motorist is willing to let the salting vehicles pass".
Then, if it no longer snows, we take care of access roads and service roads - such as the Rat-Beil-Straße.
The side lanes and side streets come last.
Mr Brauburger is well aware that this always causes some complaints.
At five o’clock in the morning, the FES pedestrian team set out to clear areas deemed dangerous and crossings as a priority.
As for bicycle paths, the FES services generally cannot deal with them.
Mr Brauburger said there was a special service in Frankfurt to monitor the condition of the bridges between 10 p.m. and 4:30 a.m.
As the ice forms very quickly on these surfaces, the salting vehicles intervene as soon as the temperature drops below 2 degrees.
The police may also use this special service if necessary.
The Cradle of Dinosaurs
The Tawa halde resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long to 1.50m high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull had sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would not have been exceptional.
But as reported by Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the earliest dinosaurs with these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at the time was part of the land of the supercontinent, the Pangea, and was towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says that the discovery of the Tawa illuminates a new day the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
Indeed, it informs us about the relationships of kinship, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
In 2006, Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other palaeontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team tells that sometimes they find a dozen bones in a day which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Trias.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
Excavations have uncovered the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the early evolution of dinosaurs.
The researchers named it Tawa after the Hopi Indian word for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional discovery: Dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare and limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all palaeontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he points out that it confirms certain theories regarding the early evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the very first dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, at what time the Sauriers were divided into three major evolutionary groups: theropods (carnivores) which include the tyrannosaurus and velociraptor that appeared later and from which descend the birds, sauropods, long-necked quadrupeds, and those related to them and the herbivores such as the ornithopian species and snithischians.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the earliest theropods.
This species has an interesting relationship of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found clues that suggest that the Tawa had small aerial bags in its bones at the level of the skull, as did the birds that are descendants of theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It appears that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small airbags in its bones.
Since the lineage of the immense sauropods also had aerial bags and a light skeleton, it may be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive known dinosaurs lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the Sauriers had appeared there.
Consequently, the three great lines of evolution split and spread from South America to the rest of the world, that is, all of the land that formed the Pangea supercontinent.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot be descended from a common ancestor who would have migrated, the researchers said.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a palaeontologist in Bonn, says there is an even older species, the Silesaur, that lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give a wrong view because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while virtually none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how did the dinosaurs manage to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they provided a relatively rare collateral line of the reptilian branch, remains a mystery today.
At the time of the Trias, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as with the ancestors of today’s crocodiles and with many other Saurians.
Towards the end of the Trias, dinosaurs spread throughout the planet, thus promoting the development of many new species while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Trias and the Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs randomly survived while other reptiles allegedly disappeared.
Or else, the dinosaurs were better suited and so they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a favored meteorite flourished in a group of animals that had also developed during the Trias and that since that time had been vegetating in the shade: these were mammals.
