The new “Silicon-Valley”
For a long time it had the reputation of a secret city, forbidden to Western visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was, under the Soviet regime, a place of search for secret weapons, under strict supervision.
Today, with its 216,000 inhabitants 37 km from the center of Moscow, the town has a reputation for being the Soviet "Silicon Valley".
Important sites for production and research in micro- and nanoelectronics are located there.
As early as September 2008, representatives of Zelenograd established ties with Riedberg, the Frankfurt Science Centre – with the university institutes and the companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There were reciprocal meetings and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg ratified a “Near Collaboration Protocol”.
The signatories were Moscow Deputy Mayor Juri Rosljak and Prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz head of project section for Frankfurt.
In 2010 representatives of FIZ and SMEs, whose strong point is scientific research, will go to Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchange
