The Worlds of Dreams
Some see, all awake, images and hear voices that no one else sees or hears.
It is not only in the mentally ill, or under the influence of drugs, that the boundaries between imagination and reality are confused.
As long as these phenomena manifest during sleep, everything is fine.
When we lie in our dark rooms, we can indulge unfettered in the wildest dreams and fantasies.
However, he who awakens and experiences a dream state, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, soon has the reputation in our Western world of being insane or drugged, or at least of being an original.
Such images and voices do not appear only in the mentally ill or under the effect of the drug.
It is our imagination that is at stake: it is the same neural activity that allows us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, but that sometimes inspires the boundaries between dream, madness and reality to merge.
A state of conscious awakening, taking the form of a dream, can present itself in the most diverse forms, in the best cases it is called visions, in the worst of folly.
But even if the trigger and effect differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the second states of shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to very similar processes.
There are hallucinations or delusions when the balance, neurotransmitters of the brain – primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine – breaks down and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts very often manifest during schizophrenic psychosis.
The earthly force of attraction no longer has power over the person.
Since antiquity, philosophers and doctors have always looked at the relationship between insanity and dreaming.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of dream-awakening; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, observed in 1861 "a great resemblance between insanity and dream", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis with all the irregularities, imaginations, delusions and sensory illusions that compose it".
It’s autumn 2001 when Henning T turns into a comic book character.
Its body is in two dimensions with screaming colors.
The earthly attraction no longer has power over it, it hovers at the edge of the ceiling.
He feels a blow.
Behind him winged, grinning devil creatures, their mouths bleeding, showing their teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy flamboyant boots, throw him against the walls, he feels pain all over his body.
Shattering, nasty voices, screaming, coming out of the walls and the radio.
He can no longer bear those voices that insult and humiliate him.
Henning T. tears two cables off his stereo, makes it a loop and attaches it to a hook attached to the ceiling.
He climbs on a baffle and passes the buckle around the neck.
He's jumping.
The loop is detached.
Let it be a lesson for you, the voices in a choir shout out to tear his eardrum off. "Go to a clinic and get treated!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last of 2 years, the first of almost 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
The diagnosis: schizo-affective psychosis, paranoid, in addition he is manic-depressive, he takes drugs against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
During psychosis I experienced terrible fears and deep despair.
Illusions are a cruel reality.
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lifetime; in psychiatric clinics this is the most common disease after depression.
In a schizophrenia crisis, the people concerned can no longer tell the difference between the inner world and the outer world, they find themselves in a state of hyper-excitation, which causes them to suffer from hallucinations, megalomania, relational madness or persecution.
It is very common to hear voices – voices that command, comment, or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also not uncommon.
The person concerned can no longer distinguish between the important and the insignificant, the brain can no longer filter the disturbing signals, the conscious is drowned under the sensations.
Just like the dream, psychosis opens the locks to a tide of ideas and fantasies coming from the deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the department of psychiatry at the CHU Heidelberg ( Allgemeine Psychiatrie im Universitätsklinikum).
The schizophrenic is in the center of the situation, all with a meaning centered on it.
At the same time he finds himself in a passive role, he is like in a dream, overcome by events and cannot act on them actively.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, manipulated.
In general they do not have the possibility of adjusting reality, illusions are a cruel reality, waking up is excluded.
Experience a hallucination once in your life.
Unlike the dream, according to Fuchs, "the sensory and spatial structure of reality that is perceived during psychosis is fundamentally preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in a real setting.
Why our brains do these kinds of cabriolets, is always a riddle for researchers.
Exceptional situations can cause everyone to temporarily lose perception of reality, according to Fuchs.
But only a small number of people will develop a psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determining factors.
The researchers assume that the people involved have tiny brain damage.
It is assumed that neuronal maturation of the brain is disturbed at an early stage of development, for example by a viral infection of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But what remains unexplained is the way the anomaly of the neural system occurs and, moreover, the fact that it does not manifest itself for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role – stress or a traumatic experience can be a trigger for psychosis, if there is a predisposition.
Likewise, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychoses because they act on neurotransmitters.
When our brains heat up.
What is crazy, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of Lübeck, is that psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and take expensive drugs to get rid of them while others buy very expensive drugs to get them.
The pleasant or unpleasant perception of illusions is often just a matter of point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and illusory image phenomena for the past ten years: last year he published his findings in a book entitled "The unreal world in our heads".
Hallucinations are part of the concomitant phenomena typical of psychoses but also an impressive number of many other pathologies.
These include mental disorders such as borderline or depression but also migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease or head trauma.
It is surprising to find that in some conditions even the brains of healthy people are subject to hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that are normally inhibited.
They take shape when the areas of the brain that deal with sensory perceptions are hyperactive or not sufficiently restrained; when our brain heats up but also when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition just like a brain injury or psychosis.
But also lack of stimulus, stress, grief of love or other exceptional mental states.
In recent studies, one-third of participants admitted to having experienced a hallucination at least once in their lives.
In summer 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and goes to high school.
A normal girl, to be honest.
