When she's in class, it happens that she can't take the class because the teacher is just presenting a new student in her eyes and ears while he's invisible to others and the teacher is obviously explaining equations on the board.
At night the apparitions are usually frightening.
When, in the darkness of her bedroom, she waits for the sleep that comes too rarely and far too late, she often cannot make the distinction if she is already awake or dreaming, if the images she sees, the grinning faces or the girl with bloody cuts on her arms and legs are in front of her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, she cries to these creatures.
She doesn't tell her parents or friends about it, they'd think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She had her bachelor's degree last year and she lives with her friend.
A year ago the hallucinations stopped.
Since she came into contact with psychologist Kasten via the internet, she knows very well that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art of despair.
When someone is socially isolated or has insufficient stimulation, the probability is great that they will have hallucinations after a certain period of time.
I guess the brain isn't busy enough to make sure there's animation.
Sarah K., the only child, was afraid of other children when she was young and often played alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at age 13 that the man she called Dad, since she was old enough to think, was not her real father.
These are the same brain areas that are active for visual and acoustic hallucinations, and for real impressions and noises, so it is very difficult for people like Sarah K to make the difference between illusion and reality.
Hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, which is why they seem so real."
For Kasten, night dreams are also a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those in acute psychoses.
Unlike schizophrenics, the mentally healthy person is able to recognize that fantasies are not real images.
That is why Kasten advises his patients to cherish hallucinations as a particular talent.
There is only one step between dreaming and hallucination.
In our overly conscientious world, unfortunately, we quickly tend to take imaginary experiments for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the psychiatric and psychotherapy clinic at Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious disease, painful but also contains something positive, creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called onioid form of experience, a particular form of dream-awakened consciousness modification.
Dreamlike experiences are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the one who lives them and that he cannot distinguish from the dream even when he is awake.
The state of consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies as for patients with polyradiculopathy who are fully aware, experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that undermines his life, with his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It is a state of mental boundary between dreaming and hallucination.
As it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world takes place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, an intense form of means and interpretation, in a situation in itself intolerable, an organizational capacity that is given to us men, so as not to sink into the void of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in the memories.
The Zurich-based art historian Peter Cornelius Classen also describes his dreamlike experiences in his book "Change of heart" as a soul-saving action.
He is 49 years old, at the time when his conscious goes on a journey of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; in the meantime, his body is doomed to remain immobile in resuscitation.
Claussen plunges into a world he has created from scratch, visits foreign places, travels back in time. He sees himself as an old man sleeping in a railway sanatorium, a robot at his bedside looking after his health.
