Contrary to dreams, memories from mental travel are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
It can even be said that they are much more distinct and more intensive than the actual experience.
The intensity of this experience makes the horizon of our other daily experiences burst, according to psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, dream-like delusions, psychoses, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of external reality are even when awake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten "can cause a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be quite rewarding.
