75% of working mothers have had work problems due to their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for younger generation women who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Feducation and career of women in Spain", carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, conducted on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers saw their professional careers limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life as a couple and the number of children, whether the woman works or not, and the type of job employed.
Those who have no activity outside the home, work part-time or have an unsteady job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier, and have more children.
In contrast, women with a stable job, mainly in the public sector, postpone the entry into couples' lives and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after they settled in a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. "These data show that women with a fixed job needed more time in their lives to get it, which has led them to push back the union and arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exerted largely influences maternity, but less the date of commencement of common life," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that increases the gap between the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child later.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, those who underwent elementary and higher education were first mothers at 25.1 and 32.1 years of age on average, respectively.
“There is also another distinction between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary education get married and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Ms. Delgado.
